In Java, we can encapuslate a field (like an array) by creating methods to access it. Here's how you could do this for your `theField` variable in the code snippet provided below using getter and setters method names as per best practices of object-oriented programming:

```java
public class A { 
    private boolean[] theField; // Declare a field with type 'boolean' array. This is our encapsulated data/field in this case, it can be accessed only within its own methods and not outside classes or packages (private).  

    public void setTheField(boolean[] newArray) { 
        if (newArray == null || newArray.length == 0){ // Checking for empty array is a best practice to prevent NullPointerException in case of an invalid input, it's not necessary here but good habit would be adding this check).  
            return;   
       }    
         theField = newArray ;  // Assign value if valid. If null or zero length then do nothing (optional) . This is how we are setting our field to a provided array, it can only happen within methods of class A and not outside this classes/packages as per encapsulation principle in OOPs concept
    }  
     public boolean[] getTheField() {  // Getter method for the 'theField' variable. This is how we are getting our field value from inside a different place (like another object). It can only happen within methods of class A and not outside this classes/packages as per encapsulation principle in OOPs concept
        return(this.theField);  // Return the 'The Field' variable, it will be returned by calling method getter from other places inside or out side our current object (class). This is how we are getting value of field and returning back to caller place/object as per encapsulation principle in OOPs concept
    }  
}  // End class A.    
```     
This way, theField can be accessed only within its own methods or classes because it's private (encapuslated). If you want access outside of this object then there are ways to do so like passing reference/object as parameter in method calls etc., but these should not generally happen unless absolutely necessary. 
Also remember, encapsulation is one way data hiding and restricting direct manipulations on the private fields (variables) from other classes or objects which can be used by them only through methods provided to us via getter/setters in this case `getTheField()` &  ` setTheField(boolean[] newArray ) method.

